    <section class="py-16 bg-white">
      <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          <h2 class="uppercase text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-4">
            Frequently Asked Questions
          </h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 mb-12">
            Your questions about new home basement issues, answered.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <!-- FAQ 1 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                Are cracks in a new basement normal?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Hairline shrinkage cracks (under 1mm, vertical) are 100% normal and expected in new concrete foundations. However, horizontal cracks, stair-step cracks in block walls, cracks wider than 3mm, or cracks that are actively leaking should be inspected by a professional immediately. "Normal" doesn't mean "harmless" — even hairline cracks can let water through under hydrostatic pressure.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ 2 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                Should I wait for the builder to fix it?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                File your Tarion claim immediately, but don't wait to act. Water damage compounds every day — mold starts growing in 24-48 hours, and structural damage worsens over time. Get an independent assessment from a waterproofing specialist (not just the builder's inspector) so you understand the severity. If the builder is dragging their feet and you're approaching warranty deadlines, consider paying for repairs yourself and documenting everything for potential reimbursement or legal action later.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ 3 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                Will waterproofing void my Tarion warranty?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                No. Tarion covers defects in the builder's workmanship and materials. Adding waterproofing protection to your basement doesn't void warranty claims for other issues (structural defects, HVAC problems, etc.). In fact, having a third-party waterproofing assessment strengthens your Tarion claim by providing independent documentation of the deficiency. Make sure to keep all invoices and reports — they may be required if you pursue a warranty claim or dispute resolution.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ 4 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                My builder says it's just condensation, not a leak. How do I know?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Do the foil test: Dry the wall completely, tape a 12" x 12" piece of aluminum foil to the damp area (seal all edges with tape), and wait 24-48 hours. If moisture appears on the room-facing side of the foil, it's condensation (humidity in your air). If moisture appears behind the foil (between foil and wall), it's water infiltration through the foundation. Take photos of the test results and include them in your Tarion claim. Infiltration requires structural repair; condensation requires a dehumidifier.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ 5 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                How long until cracks stop appearing in my new basement?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                Most concrete shrinkage cracking happens within the first 1-3 years as the concrete fully cures. Settlement cracks from soil compaction can continue to appear for 5 years as backfill soil stabilizes. After 5 years, any new cracks should be investigated immediately — they may indicate ongoing settlement issues, foundation failure, or water damage. If you're seeing new cracks after year 5, call a structural engineer for an assessment before the issue becomes severe.
              </p>
            </div>

            <!-- FAQ 6 -->
            <div class="bg-slate-50 rounded-xl p-6 border border-slate-200">
              <h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900 mb-2">
                Is it worth waterproofing a brand-new house?
              </h3>
              <p class="text-slate-700">
                If you're planning to finish your basement, <strong>absolutely yes</strong>. The cost of waterproofing now ($5K-15K) versus the cost of ripping out a finished basement later, waterproofing, and rebuilding ($25K-50K+) is a no-brainer. Even if you're not finishing immediately, addressing water issues early prevents mold, protects your home's structural integrity, maintains resale value, and gives you peace of mind. Plus, with Toronto's rebates (up to $3,400), your net cost is significantly reduced. Think of it as insurance for your largest investment.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
